      Markups
   =20
 =20
Most people who buy and sell financial assets for a living need to know how=
 much their portfolio is worth at any given time, or at least at the end of=
 the quarter. If you manage investments for clients, you have to send the c=
lients periodic statements saying =E2=80=9Cyour investments are worth $____=
_=E2=80=9D; you have to know what number to put in the blank. The clients w=
ant to know, for one thing, but also, how much you=C2=A0charge=C2=A0the cli=
ents might depend on the number that you put in the blank. If you charge th=
e clients a percentage of current assets, then you need to know what the as=
sets are currently worth. If you charge the clients a performance fee on un=
realized gains, you need to know how much the value of the assets has incre=
ased since the last statement. Even if you don=E2=80=99t manage client mone=
y, your employers will want to know how much your portfolio is worth, so th=
ey can keep an eye on risk and pay you for your performance.=C2=A0Also, tho=
ugh, many people who buy and sell financial assets for a living are fundame=
ntally in the business of looking for mispriced assets. Your job is to find=
 some situation with edge, some place where you have more expertise or pati=
ence or capacity=C2=A0than the market, some asset that you know is underval=
ued but that the market will sell to you cheap.You see the tension here, ri=
ght? The tension is:=09You think a thing is worth $100.=09Someone is sellin=
g it for $80, because they are wrong or weak.=09You buy it at $80.=09The va=
luation controller comes to you and says =E2=80=9Cfor various important pur=
poses, I need to know the current fair market value of this thing.=E2=80=9D=
=09=E2=80=9COh, $100,=E2=80=9D you say.
