 Secondary market volume for private-equity and similar funds in 2023 was $=
112 billion, according to investment bank Jefferies.The small amount of pub=
licly available data about the market shows buyers often get their stakes a=
t big discounts to the official values set by the private-equity funds=E2=
=80=99 managers. In many cases, buyers quickly mark up the stakes they acqu=
ire to the official value, no matter how little they paid for them. =E2=80=
=A6The investment funds that mark up their acquisitions benefit from instan=
t gains, which increase assets and boost fees. Strong performance numbers d=
raw in new investors.To be fair, it=E2=80=99s not like the secondary-market=
 buyers=C2=A0are just making up valuations. They are relying on=C2=A0offici=
al outside valuations, rather than their own subjective views:When the Hami=
lton Lane fund buys a stake in a private-equity fund, it relies on the valu=
ation provided by the other fund=E2=80=99s manager, known as the general pa=
rtner. =E2=80=9CWe do not adjust the GP=E2=80=99s valuation,=E2=80=9D said =
Erik Hirsch, co-chief executive officer of Hamilton Lane. =E2=80=9CWe would=
 have no basis to adjust that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0No=C2=A0basis? Not=C2=A0any=C2=
=A0basis at all? Weil can think of one:Did the Hamilton Lane fund=E2=80=99s=
 ability to buy a stake for so little raise any question about the higher v=
