      Credentials
   =20
 =20
When I was in college, my impression of management consulting was that it w=
as an industry that hired people with fancy college degrees but no specific=
 business skill or experience=C2=A0and trained them in the important busine=
ss meta-skill of hobnobbing with chief executive officers. Now it is appare=
ntly the opposite?=C2=A0Sarah Kessler reports at the New York Times that al=
l the elite employers are getting more interested in skills than in degrees=
:The idea, as the consulting firm BCG described it, is putting =E2=80=9Ccom=
petence over credentials,=E2=80=9D meaning that companies should stop looki=
ng for the right degree and instead focus on who has the right skills, rega=
rdless of how they acquired them.The pitch is basically meritocracy. And it=
=E2=80=99s everywhere. McKinsey has developed a video game to assess candid=
ates=E2=80=99 cognitive skills, which it says gives it =E2=80=9Cinsight bey=
ond the r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9 or conventional interview.=E2=80=9D And it has pub=
lished an interview prep website that a spokesperson said was necessary =E2=
=80=9Cso exceptional candidates from any source can succeed in our intervie=
ws, regardless of whether they have access to resources like a consulting c=
lub, active career services support, or an alumni network that=E2=80=99s we=
ll-connected within the consulting industry.=E2=80=9D Bank of America has p=
artnerships with 34 community colleges, and says it has hired and trained t=
housands of employees from these schools. Goldman Sachs switched to doing i=
nterviews for entry-level jobs virtually instead of only at a few top-level=
 schools. =E2=80=9CWe now encounter talent from places we previously didn=
=E2=80=99t get to,=E2=80=9D its global head of human capital wrote in 2019.=
There is a link to the video game, which as far as I can tell does not invo=
lve putting covers on manholes or filling 747s with ping-pong balls. There =
is a strange arc in certain professions, which go from being (1) real jobs =
where people with particular skills and interests get hired to do=C2=A0part=
icular sorts of work, to (2) general-purpose finishing schools for ambitiou=
s but directionless Ivy League graduates, back to (3) real jobs again. In m=
y day, investment banking and consulting were at their peak as finishing sc=
hools, but that has changed, and the transition is awkward.
