<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Markups</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most people who buy and sell financial=
 assets for a living need to know how much their portfolio is worth at any =
given time, or at least at the end of the quarter. If you manage investment=
s for clients, you have to send the clients periodic statements saying =E2=
=80=9Cyour investments are worth $_____=E2=80=9D; you have to know what num=
ber to put in the blank. The clients want to know, for one thing, but also,=
 how much you=C2=A0<em>charge=C2=A0</em>the clients might depend on the num=
ber that you put in the blank. If you charge the clients a percentage of cu=
rrent assets, then you need to know what the assets are currently worth. If=
 you charge the clients a performance fee on unrealized gains, you need to =
know how much the value of the assets has increased since the last statemen=
t. Even if you don=E2=80=99t manage client money, your employers will want =
to know how much your portfolio is worth, so they can keep an eye on risk a=
nd pay you for your performance.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also=
, though, many people who buy and sell financial assets for a living are fu=
ndamentally in the business of looking for <em>mispriced</em> assets. Your =
job is to find some situation with edge, some place where you have more exp=
ertise or patience or capacity=C2=A0than the market, some asset that you kn=
ow is undervalued but that the market will sell to you cheap.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You see the tension here, right? The tension is:</p><o=
l style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You think a thing is worth $100.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone is selling it for $80, because=
 they are wrong or weak.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You buy i=
t at $80.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The valuation controller=
 comes to you and says =E2=80=9Cfor various important purposes, I need to k=
now the current fair market value of this thing.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9COh, $100,=E2=80=9D you say.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Of course! That=E2=80=99s what it=E2=80=99s worth! That's why you boug=
ht it! (For $80.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You book $20 of =
profits, charge performance fees, etc.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">And then, oh, you know.=C2=A0Sometimes you sell the thing a week later fo=
r $100=C2=A0and everything is great.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Other times the thing never trades above $80, you sell it a year =
later for $60, and people have some questions about your valuation.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously this more or less never happens with pub=
licly traded stocks=C2=A0or Treasury bonds: When a thing has an active publ=
ic trading market, everyone understands that you mark the thing to its curr=
ent trading price, whether or not you think it=E2=80=99s underpriced. If yo=
u buy GameStop Corp. stock at $28.50 and it closes the day at $28.22, you w=
ill mark it at $28.22, whatever you might think it is actually worth.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And with illiquid hard-to-value things,=C2=A0eve=
ryone=C2=A0<em>understands=C2=A0</em>this tension, so responsible investmen=
t firms (and their accountants, risk managers,=C2=A0auditors, etc.) will ha=
ve some procedure for determining=C2=A0fair value that is not just =E2=80=
=9Cask the trader and write down whatever she says.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99ll=
 get an independent third-party valuation, or use a pricing service, or get=
 three quotes from dealers, or something. Also, firms that deal mostly in i=
lliquid hard-to-value things (venture capital, private equity, private cred=
it, etc.) are less likely to charge clients fees based on their valuations.=
 A private equity firm is more likely to charge fees based on committed cap=
ital and realized returns =E2=80=94 actual cash in and cash out =E2=80=94 w=
hile a hedge fund that trades public stocks will have an easier time chargi=
ng fees based on current asset value and unrealized returns.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Still, every so often you get stuff like this, from <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35668194.286303/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy9mdW5kcy1hcmUtYm9va2luZy1iaWctb2=
5lLWRheS13aW5kZmFsbHMtYnV5aW5nLXByaXZhdGUtZXF1aXR5LXN0YWtlcy02NjRmMzQyMw/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0edee95a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Jonathan Weil at the Wall Street J=
ournal</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The last day of Sep=
tember 2023 was very good for Hamilton Lane Private Assets Fund. It recorde=
d a 39% gain on a group of investments it bought the day before for $52 mil=
lion, giving a quick boost to the fund=E2=80=99s performance.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of the three dozen investments it bought on Sept. 29, =
nearly half had more than doubled in value on Sept. 30. The Hamilton Lane f=
und=E2=80=99s stake in a fund that focuses on Latin America rose eightfold =
in 24 hours.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Welcome to the obscure seconda=
ry market for investments in private-equity funds. The Hamilton Lane fund a=
nd others buy stakes in private-equity funds from existing investors. It is=
 a thinly traded market largely out of public view. Secondary market volume=
 for private-equity and similar funds in 2023 was $112 billion, according t=
o investment bank Jefferies.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The small amou=
nt of publicly available data about the market shows buyers often get their=
 stakes at big discounts to the official values set by the private-equity f=
unds=E2=80=99 managers. In many cases, buyers quickly mark up the stakes th=
ey acquire to the official value, no matter how little they paid for them. =
=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The investment funds that mark up=
 their acquisitions benefit from instant gains, which increase assets and b=
oost fees. Strong performance numbers draw in new investors.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be fair, it=E2=80=99s not like the second=
ary-market buyers=C2=A0are just making up valuations. They are relying on=
=C2=A0official outside valuations, rather than their own subjective views:<=
/p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the Hamilton Lane fund buy=
s a stake in a private-equity fund, it relies on the valuation provided by =
the other fund=E2=80=99s manager, known as the general partner. =E2=80=9CWe=
 do not adjust the GP=E2=80=99s valuation,=E2=80=9D said Erik Hirsch, co-ch=
ief executive officer of Hamilton Lane. =E2=80=9CWe would have no basis to =
adjust that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><e=
m>No=C2=A0</em>basis? Not=C2=A0<em>any=C2=A0</em>basis at all? Weil can thi=
nk of one:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did the Hamilton Lan=
e fund=E2=80=99s ability to buy a stake for so little raise any question ab=
out the higher valuation? =E2=80=9CAbsolutely not,=E2=80=9D Hirsch said.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously=C2=A0<em>market prices=
=C2=A0</em>have nothing to do with=C2=A0<em>value.</em></p><table class=3D"=
